inv

public abstract java.lang.String inv
State invariant, written in a string and parsed! The grammar for state invariants is as follows (and sure to change in the near future): 
 START ::= EOF | PERM EOF
 PERM  ::= POREXPR OP POREXPR
 POREXPR ::= ACCESS_PRED | JAVA_EXPR | STATE_ONLY
 ACCESS_PRED ::= ptype(ref)
               | ptype(ref) in stateInfo
               | ptype(ref,root)
               | ptype(ref,root) in stateInfo
               | ptype(ref,root,ffun,below_ffun) in stateInfo
               
 OP    ::= alt | +
         | with | &
         | tens | *
         
 JAVA_EXPR ::= PRI_EXPR JOP PRI_EXPR
 PRI_EXPR  ::= null | ref
 JOP       ::= == | !=
 
 STATE_ONLY ::= ref in stateInfo
Note that currently fraction functions (ffun and below_ffun) are just strings and are not really parsed at all. Actually, I don't even think they can be anything more than letters and numbers.

Default:
""
